      <!-- Begin .post -->
      <div id="114053762433472071" class="entry">
        <h4 class="mediumlight">
          <span class="date right">21.2.06</span>
          <a style="text-decoration:none;color:inherit;" href="http://goessner.net/2006/02/wiky-clientside-wikihtml-converter.html" title="permanent link" rel="bookmark">&#35;</a>
          <span class="entryTitle">Wiky: A Clientside Wiki/Html Converter</span>
        </h4>
        <div class="content wiki" lang="x-html"><p><img style="float:right;" src="http://goessner.net/img/wiky.png" alt="http://goessner.net/img/wiky.png" title="http://goessner.net/img/wiky.png"/>Wiky is a bidirectional Wiki markup to HTML converter written in javascript.
So there is no need for the web server to convert or even store wiki text, just plain HTML &#8212; <em>yes, I like smart clients</em>. Besides converting wiki markup, <em>Wiky</em> also can do syntax highlighting and translate LaTeX style math formulas to HTML+CSS.</p>
<p>In fact <i>Wiky + inplace editing</i> is the way I am adding content to my web pages.</p>
<p>[ <a href="http://goessner.net/articles/wiky/">read more ...</a>]</p>
<p>
<a class="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/wiki" rel="tag">Wiki</a>
<a class="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/math" rel="tag">Math</a>
<a class="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/javascript" rel="tag">Javascript</a>
</p></div>
